  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'Following the Rhyme: On Autumn Reflection with Wonchung'
  author: Shin Yeong-hee
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Suddenly I perceive the turning of seasons—
    West wind startles the ailing leaves.
    Frost gleams on the pond's pale surface,
    While heaven enters the clarity of my thatched pavilion.

    I send my verses to chase my hidden longings,
    Yet sorrow still clings from the world's entanglements.
    From the tavern keeper, on credit I take
    Weak wine in a long bottle—
    Solitude itself becomes comfort
    For what remains of my weary life.
  footnotes:
    - This poem follows the rhyme scheme of another work by Wonchung, a common practice in classical East Asian poetry where poets would compose poems matching the rhymes of previous works as a form of literary exchange and homage.
